<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38158b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38158b">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38158b"> 158(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Pert em Hru</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The spells and other texts which were written by Thoth for the benefit of the dead, and are directly connected with him, were called, according to documents written under the XIth and XVIIIth dynasties, &ldquo;Chapters of the Coming Forth by (or, into) the Day,&rdquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>. One rubric in the Papyrus of Nu (Brit. Mus. No. 10477) states that the text of the work called &ldquo;<mark>PER-T EM HRU</mark>,&rdquo; <i>i.e.</i>, &ldquo;Coming Forth (or, into) the Day,&rdquo; was discovered by a high official in the foundations of a shrine of the god Hennu during the reign of Semti, or Hesepti, a king of the Ist dynasty. <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD2"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a> (1920) 4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
